observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:

require the concerned officials or personnel to submit their comments on the observations noted;

strictly monitor the implementation of PPAs funded by LDRRMF to ensure their prompt implementation;

revisit the continuing appropriations of LDRRMF and consider the options stated above;

require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their records regularly to thresh out differences and apply adjustments, if any.

require the submission of lacking documentary requirements; and

ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF according to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1.

We recommended that the Local School Board, being the one responsible in the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under R.A. No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:

sustain its efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs and activities are optimally and fully implemented;

re-evaluate the PPAs charged under the Continuing Appropriations to determine if they are still needed, procurement and implementation-ready, and supported with available funds. Adjustments should be made as warranted;

from time to time, revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects;

for the purpose of hiring teachers chargeable against the SEF, the LSB in each province, city or municipality should utilize the list found in the Registry of Qualified Applicants (RQA); and

consider increasing the SEF budget to maximize the use of available funds.

We recommended the Municipal Budget Office to provide the different schools, thru their district Supervisors, information as to their available appropriations for their prompt implementation. In turn, the different schools should maintain a registry of appropriations, obligations and balances to have updated information that will facilitate their disbursements of funds.

We recommended:

management to require/demand the immediate settlement of all long overdue cash advances;

management to strictly comply with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97 – 002 dated February 10, 1997 in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to cause the withholding of the salary of Accountable Officers whose previous cash advances were not liquidated on or before January 20 of the ensuing year pursuant to Item 5.9 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the Rules and Regulations on the Granting, Utilization and Liquidation of Cash Advances; and

the Municipal Accountant to request for the write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 prescribing the Guidelines and Procedures on the Write-off of Dormant Receivable Accounts, Unliquidated Cash Advances, and Fund Transfers.

We recommended to the Management thru the Municipal Accountant to require all claimants / accountable persons to accomplish their liquidation reports strictly and properly to ensure proper recording of accounts and to establish accurate individual accountabilities.

We also recommended all claimants / accountable persons to:

be mindful of the details of their respective cash advances particularly the amount granted, date of grant, date due for liquidation and disbursement voucher no. / check no;

immediately submit Liquidation Reports and their supporting documents within reglementary period to avoid possible loss and for their prompt recording in the books of accounts;

ensure the proper accomplishment of Liquidation Reports (LR) by indicating all required particulars and details. In case of refunds, a LR should still be accomplished and submitted to the accounting office along with a photocopy of the Official Receipt;

attach and submit all supporting documents for each LR; and

maintain a personal copy for each Liquidation Report submitted to the accounting office for future reference.

We recommended that management require:

the creation of an inventory committee consisting of representatives from different concerned offices to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality who will prepare the necessary Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (RPCRNS) using the form in Annex C of COA Circular 2015-008. The RPCRNS should be reconciled with the Accounting and GSO records;

the Municipal Engineer to provide the Accountant and the General Service Officer with the complete description and segregation of road components for those with data on construction cost. For those not posted in the registry but without identified cost and those included in the RPCRNS but not in the registry, the fair value must be used in determining the cost of road components and thereafter shall provide the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

the Municipal Accountant to depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and accordingly adjust the amount recorded in the Road Network account supported by the RPCRNS, Registry Infrastructure for Roads and working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement cost per registry. Subsequently, at the end of each year, a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation for each depreciable road component must be prepared as basis for recording depreciation expenses and the required Local Road Network Ledger Card for each road network shall likewise be maintained; and

the MGSO at the end or every accounting period to render a Report on Local Road Network using the pro-forma schedule in Annex A of same Circular and maintain local road inventory, Road Map and complete Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

We recommended management to

Instruct the Municipal Accountant that all regular purchases shall be coursed thru the inventory account and issuances thereof shall be recorded as they take place, except for those purchased out of the petty cash fund as required in Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the semestral, physical count of inventory items by type, and prepare the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI). Thereafter, submit a copy to the Auditor, pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Require all deliveries of items purchased by the LGU to be accepted first by the General Services Office before the inspection thereof pursuant to Section 118 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Instruct the General Services Office to consolidate weekly the Requisition Issue Slip using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued. Based on the SSMI, a JEV shall be prepared by the Municipal Accountant pursuant to Section 121 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Prepare the necessary adjustment to reflect the actual correct balances thereof. Likewise, both records of the Municipal Accountant’s Office and General Services Office should be adjusted accordingly in order to present fairly the financial position of the Municipality.

We recommended:

the Local Chief Executive to enforce the settlement of the above audit disallowances which have become final and executory and in compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-006;

the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the disallowances which have not yet become final and executory;

the Municipal Accountant to review previous records which served as the bases of the Accounting Office in recording Receivables-Disallowances in order to determine the persons liable and other details necessary in the monitoring of receivables;

the Municipal Treasurer to immediately notify the Audit Team regarding settlement of disallowances and submit proof of settlement thereof for prompt issuance of NSSDC, or in the alternative, submit a monthly summary of settlement of disallowances; and

the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries or any amount due to the persons liable for the settlement of their liabilities, unless a request for installment payment was approved by the Prosecution and Litigation Office (PLO) of the Commission on Audit pursuant to COA Resolution No. 2017-021.

We recommended that management:
ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to assure that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities are achieved;
revisit continuing appropriations of the LDRRMF and consider options such as reprogramming, transfer to a special trust fund, or reversion to the general fund for unutilized balances from previous years;
require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their records regularly to thresh out differences and apply adjustments, if any.
ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF according to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1; and
continuously comply with pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the recording, utilization and reporting of LDRRMF.

